First, let's find the symmetric difference of A and B, denoted as A Δ B. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection.

A Δ B = (A ∪ B) - (A ∩ B) = ({1, 2, 3} ∪ {2, 3, 4}) - ({1, 2, 3} ∩ {2, 3, 4})
A Δ B = {1, 4}

Now, let's find the symmetric difference of (A Δ B) Δ A and A Δ (B Δ A).

1. (A Δ B) Δ A = ({1, 4} Δ {1, 2, 3})
(A Δ B) Δ A = ({1, 4} ∪ {1, 2, 3}) - ({1, 4} ∩ {1, 2, 3})
(A Δ B) Δ A = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {1}
(A Δ B) Δ A = {2, 3, 4}

2. A Δ (B Δ A) = {1, 2, 3} Δ ({2, 3, 4} Δ {1, 2, 3})
B Δ A = ({2, 3, 4} ∪ {1, 2, 3}) - ({2, 3, 4} ∩ {1, 2, 3})
B Δ A = {1, 4}
A Δ (B Δ A) = {1, 2, 3} Δ {1, 4}
A Δ (B Δ A) = ({1, 2, 3} ∪ {1, 4}) - ({1, 2, 3} ∩ {1, 4})
A Δ (B Δ A) = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {1}
A Δ (B Δ A) = {2, 3, 4}

As we can see, both expressions (A Δ B) Δ A and A Δ (B Δ A) are equal to {2, 3, 4}. This demonstrates that the symmetric difference of two sets is associative.
